column14:
Who were "your people" during childhood?

Who were the three people who you interacted with the most during K-12 education? How are you related (parents, friends, etc)? 
Did your political beliefs align with this persons(s)?
Did you know if they identified with a political party? 

Sample response: 
My closest people were my mom (strong democrat), friend (strong republican), and friend (NA). I don't know if all of them are committed to a political party, but I do know that my mom is part of the Democratic Farmer Labor Party in MN and has voted more liberal since Donald Trump took office. With my friend we stopped talking about politics after X because our relationship got to be too timid whereas with my other friend we ended up being closer because we shared the same beliefs after X happened.
column15:
Who are “your people”?

Who are the three people who you interact with the most? How are you related (parents, friends, etc)? 
Do your political beliefs align with this persons(s)?
Do you know if they identify what political party is? 

Sample response: 
My closest people are my mom (strong democrat), roommate (strong republican), and cousin (moderate). I don't know if all of them are committed to a political party, but I do know that my mom is part of the Democratic Farmer Labor Party in MN and has voted more liberal since Donald Trump took office. With my roommate I try to avoid talking about politics, so I am unsure if they are committed to a political party, and same for my cousin.

column14: My closest people were my parents and a friend. My parents have never voted republican , though my mom is more strongly a democrat. I had occasional disagreements with them growing up, but they rarely became particularly heated, and we generally agreed on what we saw as the "important things," generally social issues. Neither of them are members of any party. My friend was also a strong democrat, though stronger than me. Several arguments were had relating to that, one of which almost ended our friendship.
column15: My closest three people are a local friend, a long distance friend, and my mother. None are committed to a political party. My mothers political beliefs have remained the same, and we rarely discuss them. I never discuss political subjects with my local friend, partially out of a suspicion that it would lead to arguments, as I suspect him to be further right than me, though likely not a republican. The long distance friend is the opposite; I suspect her to be further left than me, particularly on social issues. I try to avoid talking about it with her as well, but her occasional statements that I would consider misandrist do sometimes tempt me to start arguments.
column16: Rarely (voting during presidential elections)

column14: The people closest to me during my childhood were my parents. My mom is a strong democrat. My father is a democrat with some republican beliefs. I agree with my mom on most everything she thinks in regards to politics. There are many things I do not agree with in regards to my dad and his political thoughts.
column15: The people closest to me is my mom and two close friends. All of which are strong democrats. I feel as though I can talk to all of them about politics. My beliefs align with each of these people.
column16: Moderately  (I vote in every presidential and sometimes vote in state and local elections)

column14: My closest people were my mom and dad (centrists, slightly conservative leaning) and two friends (one slightly conservative leaning, one strongly democratic). My political beliefs didn't always align with my friends', typically didn't talk much about politics, would just notice some differences in reaction to headlines/current events.
column15: My closest friends are my mom and dad (centrists, slightly conservative leaning) and a handful of friends who are almost entirely all strong democrats, but do have one friend who is strongly republican. Again, politics aren't typically a subject of discussion but with current events I notice some differences between our perspectives and reactions.
column16: Moderately  (I vote in every presidential and sometimes vote in state and local elections)

column14: My closest friends were other students and most of them were very liberal and I agreed with many of the claims they made, but sometimes did not understand why they thought the way they did. I was very anti-conservative with them, especially in high school. Most of my friends identified with the Democratic Party, but I've had boyfriends who identify with the Republican Party.
column15: My friend Ellie (strong democrat), my boyfriend Brenden (Moderate/Republican), and my other friend Elleigh (Moderate). My political beliefs are very similar to Elleigh and Brenden, and I am hit or miss with agreeing on what my friend Ellie believes. I talk about politics all of the time, especially because I am a political science major and I like to hear what everyone has to say. Although, it can get difficult when someone (on either side) is super radical.
column16: Moderately  (I vote in every presidential and sometimes vote in state and local elections)

column14: My closest people were my parents and my brother. We lived in Venezuela until 2017 when we had to leave the country due to the government being a socialist dictatorship. This, of course, meant that both me and my parents were and still are right leaning since socialism and communism ruined the place we grew up in.
column15: My closest people are my girlfriend, in campus friends, and friends from high school I talk to everyday. They are all strong democrats and they see me as more of a moderate person since I have different perspectives as them in regards to real world experiences.
column16: Never

column14: My closest people were my mom (strong republican), friend (strong republican), and friend (strong liberal).My mom does not vote by choice, my Republican friend is aligned with the Republican Party since she was able to vote and my democrat friend is not as strongly tied to the party. My beliefs align with my mother and my R friend but I don’t discuss politics with my D friend. I was aware of my friends political affiliation.
column15: My closest people are Friend Democrat, Friend Democrat and Friend Republican. They are all aligned with their set parties. I do not talk politics with my D friends because we do not agree on Palestine among other issues but I know they are committed to their parties.

column14: my closest people would be my mom, my dad and my friend. My mom is a proclaimed democrat, and leans liberal on most topics however has some centrist ideals. My dad on the other hand claims to be a complete centrist, however has more conser
column15: My closest people in k-12 would be my mom, my dad, and my friend. My mom is a democrat and for the most part votes democrat. She has mostly liberal ideals but some centrist tendencies on certain topics. My dad on the other hand claims to be a centrist- but he defiantly leans more conservatively. He would be a republican but does not agree with todays definition of a republican with Trumps era. So he claims to be a centrist (but is really a republican). My friend is a republican through and through. She is a trump supporter and has very conservative beliefs- which doesn't make sense to me because she is gay and a nonbeliever in the church.

column14: My people were my mom, my dad, and my brother. We all had pretty similar political beliefs. We all were pretty neutral and thought there was good arguments on both sides.
column15: My closest people are still my parents my mom, my dad and my brother. I do not think our political beliefs have changed much. column14: The three people I interacted with the most when I was young were my parents (Democrats)and my brother (Democrat). My brother has very strong political beliefs and is a Democrat, my parents are also Democrats. I was influenced by that a lot and now consider myself a Democrat.

column14: My closest people were my mom (strong democrat), dad (moderate democrat) and friend W (indepedent - maybe more libertarian). My parents are both Democratic voters and while they may vote differently in primaries and local elections, they always support democratic candidates in federal and state elections. My friend isn't a registered voter and usually has a split ticket between dems and the gop. I align pretty closely with my father in that I vote democratic but I'm moderate on many issues. My friend has had some influence on my politics  by shifting me more to the right economically.
column15: My closest people are my mom (strong democrat), my friend W (independent) and my friend (strong democrat). Whenever I'm home I usually will end up discussing news or politics with her, as she's still an involved democrat and we still share a lot of political beliefs. My friend W and I have gotten further apart on my issues over time but we still share some common beliefs, but I think now we vote pretty differently. My friend G is pretty liberal and politically involved on campus. While they're more active than I am I agree with a lot of their beliefs and we vote similarly.
column16: Moderately  (I vote in every presidential and sometimes vote in state and local elections)

column14: My closest people were my mom(democrat), my friend Micah (NA), and my friend Bri(NA). My friends are into politics and don't have a side with any political party. Growing up with my Mom, I would say she played a large role in influencing me to become a democrat similar to her, but I wouldn't consider myself one sided either.
column15: My closest people are my mom(democrat), my girlfriend (NA), and my roommate (strong republican). Again, I wouldn't say any of their political beliefs match with my own, primarily because I do not have one. I am still working on trying to get myself into politics and the world, but it is hard especially being from Hawaii which is so isolated from the mainland and other states, that it almost feels like the impact at home doesn't have to do with us a whole lot, which I am sure is untrue, but I have never been educated about any politics growing up.

column14: My closest people were my older sister (strong democrat), my mom (democrat). My political beliefs align with theirs. I'm not very big on politics in general so they definitely care about politics more than I do.
column15: My closest people are my sister (strong democrat), my best friend (NA) and my cousin (NA). My political beliefs align with my sister. I'm not sure about my best friend and my cousin because we don't really talk about politics. Also, my cousin is younger than I am.

All my friends never took an interest in politics so there were no disputes about which parties we chose.
column15: My closest people are my girlfriend, my friend on campus, and a friend in another country. All of them don't believe in any party beliefs except they are in favor of liberal ideals.

column14: My closest people were my friend (NA) and my parents (both moderates/neoliberals). My friend ended up developing libertarian political ideals and we greatly enjoyed discussing politics together through high school, though I don't know that he aligns with either major party as the DFL tends to be too fiscally left-leaning for him and the GOP is too socially conservative. My parents are both affiliated with the DFL. My own political inclinations tend more leftwards than all mentioned above.
column15: My closest people are my roommate (left-leaning), my younger sister (progressive democrat) and my friend (leftist). I believe my roommate votes with the Democratic party in his state -- as does my friend, given the binary options presented by our current voting system -- and my sister is not yet old enough to vote, but holds a mix of left-leaning and reactionary politics. My political beliefs tend to align with my friend and roommate
column16: Continuously (I am continously involved in staying up to date with all elections: local, state, and national)

column14: My people growing up were definitely my mom (republican), my friend Kate (NA), and my other friend Annie (NA). I'm not sure if any of them are committed to any political party, but I know my mom consistently votes republican. Me and my mom's political views are probably the closest out of anyone in my family, but I think I am definitely more left-leaning than her. My friends definitely have similar political views to me which are more left leaning, but when it comes to voting I know they were both raising in households that were more republican and therefore they might be more likely to vote red because of familial pressure/being unsure of who else to vote for.
column15: My closest people now are my mom (republican), my friend (moderate), and my other friend (more liberal). I know both my friends are not committed to political parties, but would both lean blue in voting, whereas my mom would lean red. I talk about politics a lot with my friends and we don't have the exact same views on everything, but we definitely tend to take similar stances on most things. And even when we disagree we are all mature enough to see that people are entitled to their own beliefs. I would say taking about politics with them has made us closer because we are all kind of navigating it together which is helpful. I've had more recent conversations with my mom about political topics and I think we definitely have gotten more aligned in our beliefs as we have gotten older, but not identical.
column16: Moderately  (I vote in every presidential and sometimes vote in state and local elections)

column14: My closest 3: oldest brother (NA politics), teammate (republican), and school friend (democratic). column15: My dad (republican), teammate (liberal) and classmate (NA). My political beliefs align somewhat with each one, but nothing on the extremes.

I slowly became more radical as I grew up and I believe my father began to take after me in this respect.

I am more radical than these people, I identify as a democratic socialist and am in favor of democratic control of the economy.
